SIMPLE: sire
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sire
<hw>Sire</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>sire</ets>,
originally, an older person. See <er>Sir</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
lord, master, or other person in authority. See <er>Sir</er>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pain and distress, sickness and ire,⟦br⟧
And melancholy that angry <qex>sire</qex>,⟦br⟧
Be of her palace senators.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. of R.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tittle of respect formerly used in speaking to
elders and superiors, but now only in addressing a sovereign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A father; the head of a family; the
husband.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jankin thet was our <qex>sire</qex> [i.e., husband].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And raise his issue, like a loving <qex>sire</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A creator; a maker; an author; an
originator.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] was the <qex>sire</qex> of an immortal strain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The male parent of a beast; -- applied especially to
horses; <as>as, the horse had a good <ex>sire</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sire</xex> is often used in composition; as in
grand<xex>sire</xex>, grandfather; great-grand<xex>sire</xex>,
great-grandfather.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sire
<hw>Sire</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sired</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Siring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To beget; to procreate; -- used of
beasts, and especially of stallions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Siredon</ent>⟦br⟧
